> ok. so 6 o'clock represents I or me. 12 is 'you' - 9 is 'he/she/it' and 3 
is 'them or they' - the idea of the game is to kind of 'light up' the 
circles during translations of sentences like 

⏺ Got it! So the circles represent verb conjugation subjects:

  - 12 o'clock (Red) = "you" (tú)
  - 3 o'clock (Green) = "they/them" (ellos/ellas)
  - 6 o'clock (Blue) = "I/me" (yo)
  - 9 o'clock (Orange) = "he/she/it" (él/ella)

  And the game lights up the corresponding circle when translating sentences
   - so if you hear/see "I run" → the 6 o'clock blue circle lights up, "They
   eat" → 3 o'clock green lights up, etc.

  This is a great way to drill verb conjugation visually!

  How should the "lighting up" work? Some options:
  1. Glow/pulse animation - circle gets brighter, maybe scales up slightly
  2. Flash - quick bright flash then fade
  3. Ring expansion - a ring radiates outward from the circle
  4. Fill intensity - circle goes from dim to full saturation

  And what triggers it - clicking, keyboard, audio, or showing sentences to
  translate?

> yes, but it's more for learning structure like 'te necesito' -> 'I need 
you' . So we need to add a circle for 'we/us' maybe right to the left of the
 'I' circle... 

⏺ Ah, I see! So you can show relationships like "te necesito" where the
  subject (I) and object (you) both light up - showing the structure of
  who's doing what to whom.

  Let me add a "we/us" (nosotros) circle to the left of the "I" circle:

