⏺ Done! Refresh to see:

  - Text now appears in the center of the main circle (Spanish phrase in
  bold, English translation below in gray)
  - Serial lighting: Subject lights up first (at 400ms), then object lights
  up (at 900ms)

  So for "Te necesito" (I need you):
  1. First the I circle (blue, 6 o'clock) lights up
  2. Then the you circle (red, 12 o'clock) lights up

  Try it out!

> wow. this is pretty powerful :) 

⏺ That's great to hear! It really does make the sentence structure click
  visually - seeing the subject light up first, then the object, maps
  perfectly to how Spanish pronouns work.

  A few ideas if you want to take it further:

  1. Add labels to the small circles (yo, tú, él/ella, nosotros, ellos) so
  learners know what each position means
  2. Draw an arrow/line between subject and object as they light up to show
  the relationship
  3. Randomize the phrases instead of sequential
  4. Add a "reveal" mode - show just the Spanish first, let user guess, then
   show English + animation
  5. Different verb categories - reflexive verbs (me lavo), indirect objects
   (te doy un libro), etc.
  6. Sound - pronounce the phrase when it appears

  What direction interests you?

> yes all of these sound good. I think we actually add English labels in the
 circles. We don't need an arrow. What do you mean by randomize? Sound would
 be amazing, but first I want to think about tenses...we have past, present 
and future. I was thinking we could have a flash of color on the right for 
the future tense, in the middle for present and on the left for past (the 
two forms)...I don't know if this would be like dividing the page into 3 
columns? And flash a light color for whichever it is? 

⏺ I love the tense visualization idea! So the main circle area gets a subtle
   flash:
  - Left side = past (preterite/imperfect)
  - Center = present
  - Right side = future

  Let me add the English labels to the circles first, then add the tense
  flash system:

