⏺ Done! Created a 2x2 grid with:

  S-Curve (Sigmoid) - Green
  - Tech adoption, population growth, learning, market saturation, disease
  spread

  Inverted U (Bell Curve) - Orange
  - Stress vs performance, drug dosage, exercise benefits, Laffer curve

  Exponential Growth - Red
  - Compound interest, viral spread, Moore's Law, crypto bubbles

  Power Law - Purple
  - Wealth distribution, city populations, Zipf's law, social media
  followers

  Each has axes, a smooth curve, and real-world examples below. Take a look!

> any others you can think of, or are those the main ones? 

⏺ Those are the big four, but here are a few more that show up frequently:

  Logarithmic - Opposite of exponential. Fast early gains, then diminishing
  returns. (Perceived loudness, Richter scale, human perception of
  differences)

  J-Curve - Dips before rising. (Private equity returns, currency
  devaluation effects, organizational change)

  Diminishing Returns - Similar to log but emphasizing the plateau.
  (Fertilizer on crops, hours worked vs productivity, practice after
  mastery)

  Hyperbolic Discounting - How we value things over time. (Why we prefer
  $100 now vs $110 next week, procrastination)

  Bathtub Curve - High at ends, low in middle. (Product failure rates -
  early defects, long stable period, then wear-out)

  Long Tail - Related to power law but emphasizing the tail. (Netflix
  catalog, Amazon products, music streaming)

  Step Function - Sudden jumps. (Phase transitions, tipping points, paradigm
   shifts)

  Logistic Decay - S-curve but going down. (Technology obsolescence, market
  share loss)

  Want me to add any of these to the page? I'd suggest Logarithmic, J-Curve,
   and Diminishing Returns as the most useful additions - they come up
  constantly in business/life contexts.

